{"timestamp":"2026-03-14T03:00:48.246Z","level":"WARN","message":"codex stderr","iteration":11,"chunk":"codex\nUpdated the claim persistence path in [taskFile.ts](/abs/path/c:/Users/ben.jones/source/repos/Ralph/RalphDex/ralph-codex-vscode-starter/src/ralph/taskFile.ts#L214) so claim mutations now write through a temp file, `fsync` that temp file, then swap it into place while still holding the existing file lock. That keeps the current acquire/release semantics intact, but makes the locked write path less prone to leaving a truncated claim file behind if the process is interrupted mid-write.\n\nI also extended [taskFile.test.ts](/abs/path/c:/Users/ben.jones/source/repos/Ralph/RalphDex/ralph-codex-vscode-starter/test/taskFile.test.ts#L598) with the concurrent lock regression that was already in flight and added a cleanup regression at [taskFile.test.ts](/abs/path/c:/Users/ben.jones/source/repos/Ralph/RalphDex/ralph-codex-vscode-starter/test/taskFile.test.ts#L646) to verify successful claim acquire/release cycles do not leave `*.lock` or temp-write artifacts behind.\n\nValidation: focused claim coverage passed with `npm run compile:tests && node --require ./test/register-vscode-stub.cjs --test --test-isolation=none ./out-test/test/taskFile.test.js`. The required repo-wide `npm test` still fails in this environment with unrelated `spawn EPERM` errors in existing CLI/integration tests that launch child processes and `git`, so I could not get a clean full-suite pass here.\n\nAssumption/blocker: I treated the current claim API shape as the durable partial implementation and hardened the on-disk write path rather than redesigning the API. Known limitation: full `npm test` remains blocked by the sandboxed process-spawn restriction, not by the claim changes.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"selectedTaskId\": \"T24.1.2\",\n  \"requestedStatus\": \"done\",\n  \"progressNote\": \"Hardened task claim persistence in src/ralph/taskFile.ts by writing claim-file updates through a synced temp file